# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler

## Context

The Mistral Instruct v0.3 format is a common chat template used by models such as
`mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3`. It uses `[INST]`/`[/INST]` markers around user
turns, inlines system messages at the start of the first user turn (inside the markers),
and appends `</s>` directly after each assistant reply — without the `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`
tags introduced in Mistral v7/Ministral-3.

Currently, a Jinja template string for this format that reaches `llm_chat_detect_template`
falls through all Mistral-specific checks and lands in the Llama-2 fallback branch, which
is incorrect. A named template `"mistral-instruct-v3"` does not exist in the lookup map.
This plan adds the complete named-template + auto-detection + handler implementation with
zero changes to any existing handler bodies or function signatures.

---

## Files to Change

| File | Change type |
|---|---|
| `src/llama-chat.h` | Add one new enum value (additive) |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` | Add map entry, detection branch, handler block |

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — Add enum value in `src/llama-chat.h`

Insert the new value immediately **before** `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN` (currently line 61).
Do not touch any other line.

```cpp
// after LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_SOLAR_OPEN (line 60), before LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN (line 61)
LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3,
```

Result in the enum (excerpt):
```cpp
    LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_SOLAR_OPEN,
    LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3,   // ← NEW
    LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN,
```

---

### Step 2 — Register the named template in `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATES` map (`src/llama-chat.cpp`)

Insert after the `"mistral-v7-tekken"` entry (currently line 38). This is a pure addition
to the map initialiser list; no existing entry is touched.

```cpp
{ "mistral-v7-tekken", LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_V7_TEKKEN },
{ "mistral-instruct-v3", LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3 },  // ← NEW
```

---

### Step 3 — Add auto-detection logic in `llm_chat_detect_template` (`src/llama-chat.cpp`)

The detection lives inside the outer branch that fires when the template starts with
`"mistral"` or contains `[INST]` (line 103). Within that branch, after the existing
`else if` that catches v1/v3/v3-tekken patterns (line 121), the code falls into an
`else { ... }` block that handles Llama-2 variants.

Insert a new `else if` **between** the v1/v3 check and the Llama-2 `else` block:

```
BEFORE (existing structure, simplified):

if (tmpl_contains("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]")) {
    return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_V7;
} else if (tmpl_contains("' [INST] ' + system_message")
        || tmpl_contains("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]")) {
    // returns V1 / V3 / V3_TEKKEN
} else {
    // llama-2 variants ...
}

AFTER (structure with new branch inserted):

if (tmpl_contains("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]")) {
    return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_V7;
} else if (tmpl_contains("' [INST] ' + system_message")
        || tmpl_contains("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]")) {
    // existing v1 / v3 / v3-tekken — UNCHANGED
} else if (tmpl_contains("'[INST] ' + message['content']")) {   // ← NEW BRANCH
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3: uses [INST] but no [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
    // The literal "'[INST] ' + message['content']" appears in the
    // official Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 Jinja template and
    // distinguishes it from both Ministral-3 ([SYSTEM_PROMPT] absent)
    // and the Llama-2 family (<<SYS>> absent).
    return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3;
} else {
    // llama-2 variants — UNCHANGED
}
```

The new `else if` condition is:
```cpp
} else if (tmpl_contains("'[INST] ' + message['content']")) {
    return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3;
}
```

**Why this pattern is safe:**
- `'[INST] ' + message['content']` (no leading space before the bracket, using
  `message['content']` directly) appears verbatim in the Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3
  Jinja template but **not** in the v1 template (`' [INST] ' + system_message`),
  not in v3/v3-tekken (`[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` gated), and not in Llama-2 templates
  (`<<SYS>>` / `bos_token + '[INST]` markers).
- All existing branches are untouched.

---

### Step 4 — Add handler implementation in `llm_chat_apply_template` (`src/llama-chat.cpp`)

Insert a new `else if` block **after** the existing MISTRAL_V1/V3/V3_TEKKEN handler
(which ends at the closing `}` of the block around line 291) and **before** the
LLAMA_2 handler (which starts around line 292). This is a pure addition; no existing
handler body is modified.

```cpp
} else if (tmpl == LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3) {
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 format:
    //   - system message is prepended to the first user turn (inside [INST]/[/INST])
    //   - user turn:      [INST] {content} [/INST]
    //   - assistant turn: {content}</s>
    // See: https://huggingface.co/mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3
    std::string sys_prompt;
    for (auto message : chat) {
        std::string role(message->role);
        std::string content(message->content);
        if (role == "system") {
            sys_prompt = content;
        } else if (role == "user") {
            ss << "[INST] ";
            if (!sys_prompt.empty()) {
                ss << sys_prompt << "\n\n";
                sys_prompt.clear();
            }
            ss << content << " [/INST]";
        } else {
            // assistant (or any other role)
            ss << content << "</s>";
        }
    }
    if (add_ass) {
        ss << "[INST] ";
    }
```

**Exact location**: the insertion point is the closing `}` of the MISTRAL_V1/V3/V3_TEKKEN
block (line ~291 in the current file). Change:

```cpp
        }
    } else if (
            tmpl == LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_LLAMA_2
```

to:

```cpp
        }
    } else if (tmpl == LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3) {
        // ... new handler body above ...
    } else if (
            tmpl == LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_LLAMA_2
```

---

## Expected Rendered Output

For input `[system="You are a helpful assistant", user="Hello", assistant="Hi there", user="Who are you"]` with `add_ass=true`:

```
[INST] You are a helpful assistant\n\nHello [/INST]Hi there</s>[INST] Who are you [/INST][INST] 
```

---

## Verification

1. **Named-template lookup** — run with `--chat-template mistral-instruct-v3`; verify
   it no longer throws `std::out_of_range`.

2. **Auto-detection** — call `llm_chat_detect_template()` with the raw Jinja string from
   `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3`'s `tokenizer_config.json`; assert the return
   value is `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3`.

3. **Handler output** — call `llm_chat_apply_template(LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3, ...)`
   with a `[system, user, assistant, user]` sequence; verify:
   - System text appears inside first `[INST] ... [/INST]` block, separated from user
     text by `\n\n`.
   - Assistant turn ends with `</s>` (no trimming).
   - Subsequent user turns have plain `[INST] content [/INST]` (no system prefix).
   - `add_ass=true` appends a bare `[INST] `.

4. **Regression** — run the existing `tests/test-chat-template` suite; confirm all
   existing named templates (especially `mistral-v3`, `mistral-v7`, `llama2`) still
   produce their expected outputs unchanged.

5. **No [SYSTEM_PROMPT] clash** — ensure a template string containing `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`
   still routes to `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_V7`, not the new handler.

